---
import Base from "../../layouts/Base.astro";

const title = "SplatForge — Hosted Neural preset";
const description =
  "On-demand per-scene neural codec. Fits a tiny hash-grid hyperprior to your scene on an A100 and returns encoded bytes. ~9-10 min per bicycle-scale scene, ~$0.35. Endpoint-native N=3 on bicycle: 4.18x neural-byte ratio at +4.29 dB delta-PSNR vs the opacity-prune baseline.";
---

<Base title={title} description={description}>
  <nav class="nav" aria-label="Primary">
    <a href="/" class="nav-brand">
      <span class="dot" aria-hidden="true"></span>
      splatforge
    </a>
    <div class="nav-links">
      <a href="/#docs">Quickstart</a>
      <a href="/bench">SplatBench</a>
      <a href="/import">Import</a>
      <a href="/#try" aria-current="page">Try it</a>
    </div>
  </nav>

  <h1>Hosted Neural preset</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    The <code>hosted-neural</code> preset fits a tiny hash-grid hyperprior to
    your scene on an A100 at request time and returns the encoded artifact.
    There is no shared trained model — every invocation runs a per-scene
    optimization, which is why outdoor scenes (where the scene-class statistics
    are heavier-tailed) win the biggest compression at the highest fidelity.
  </p>

  <h2>What it does</h2>
  <p>
    For each scene the encoder:
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li>
      Parses the source 3DGS PLY and the supplied cameras + photos.
    </li>
    <li>
      Trains a 4-level voxel-hash position encoder feeding a 64-hidden MLP
      that predicts a discrete-logistic <code>(μ, σ)</code> per quantized
      splat-attribute scalar (means / scales / quats / opacity / SH).
    </li>
    <li>
      Co-tunes the splat parameters against the source photos under the
      joint <code>mse + λ·bits + λ·opacity</code> loss, with an adaptive
      <code>λ_bits</code> targeting a chosen byte budget.
    </li>
    <li>
      Returns a <code>.tar</code> containing the encoded PLY, the
      per-scene hyperprior weights (<code>hyperprior.safetensors</code>),
      and a summary with the achieved compression ratio + ΔPSNR.
    </li>
  </ol>

  <h2>When to use it</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Any scene where ~9-10 min of encode-time is acceptable.</strong>
      The preset works on any scene class; outdoor captures (bicycle,
      garden, stump) just happen to benefit the most because the v0.2
      opacity-prune baseline leaves a lot of dB on the table there.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Outdoor ROI (endpoint-native N=3).</strong> Bicycle outdoor
      currently lands at ~4.2× neural-byte ratio with +4.3 dB ΔPSNR vs the
      opacity-prune baseline. Indoor scenes (bonsai, kitchen) hit ~3-5× at
      ~+1 dB on the same RD schedule.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>You want the bytes today, decoder later.</strong> The
      Rust-side decoder is a separate task; the artifact ships the
      encoded PLY + per-scene weights so you can store the bitstream
      now and decode in a future release without re-encoding.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Cost model</h2>
  <p>
    Cost is dominated by the A100 training pass. A typical bicycle-scale
    scene (~855 MB Inria PLY) runs <strong>~545 s on A100</strong> (1000
    iterations, 512 px supervision) plus ~60-180 s of tar packaging and
    blob upload, for an end-to-end wall of <strong>~9-12 min/scene</strong>
    and a Modal compute bill of roughly <strong>$0.32-$0.40/scene</strong>
    at the published A100 rate. Smaller indoor scenes land lower; the
    per-MB slope is small because the iteration budget dominates wall-clock.
  </p>

  <h2>Validated numbers (N=3 endpoint-native, bicycle outdoor)</h2>
  <p>
    Per <a href="/#bench">Principle 2 (render-PSNR + N=3 multi-seed)</a>,
    every codec rung's headline claim is N=3 multi-seed on real-photo
    corpus. Numbers below are <strong>endpoint-native</strong> — fired
    directly at the deployed <code>splatforge-hosted-neural</code> Modal
    app via <code>run_hosted_neural</code>, not at a private research
    branch. Bicycle outdoor at <code>target_neural_ratio = 0.05</code>,
    1000 iterations, 512 px supervision:
  </p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Seed</th>
        <th>Compression ratio</th>
        <th>ΔPSNR (dB)</th>
        <th>Splats out</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>0</td><td>3.84×</td><td>+4.186</td><td>1,808,054</td></tr>
      <tr><td>1</td><td>4.39×</td><td>+4.382</td><td>1,808,054</td></tr>
      <tr><td>2</td><td>4.31×</td><td>+4.306</td><td>1,808,054</td></tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Mean ± stdev</strong></td>
        <td><strong>4.18× ± 0.29</strong></td>
        <td><strong>+4.29 ± 0.10</strong></td>
        <td>1,808,054</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p class="footnote">
    The earlier 7.54× / +8.39 dB cell on this page was a source-code
    median measured on the private <code>research/neural-codec-v0.1-m3</code>
    branch (commit <code>aaadf09</code>). The deployed endpoint at
    <code>deploy/hosted-neural-endpoint</code> (commit <code>ff9b700</code>)
    consistently produces roughly half the compression and half the
    ΔPSNR — a documented drift between the M3 research cell and the
    productized encoder. Numbers above are the endpoint-native N=3
    fired on 2026-05-16; raw run records are in
    <code>splatforge-private/worktrees/sf-155-hosted-neural-n3/tasks/scripts/task-155/results/n3_endpoint_runs.json</code>.
  </p>

  <h2>Indoor numbers</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Scene</th>
        <th>target_neural_ratio</th>
        <th>N</th>
        <th>Median ratio</th>
        <th>Median ΔPSNR</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>bonsai (indoor)</td><td>0.10</td><td>2</td><td>3.39×</td><td>+0.97</td></tr>
      <tr><td>bonsai (indoor)</td><td>0.05</td><td>3</td><td>4.35×</td><td>+1.06</td></tr>
      <tr><td>bonsai (indoor)</td><td>0.02</td><td>3</td><td>4.63×</td><td>+1.03</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Input shapes</h2>
  <p>
    The neural fit needs the source photos because it co-tunes the splat
    parameters against re-renders. Two ways to invoke:
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <strong>Bundle mode (<code>.tar</code> / <code>.tar.gz</code> /
      <code>.tgz</code>).</strong>
      The archive must contain <code>point_cloud.ply</code>,
      <code>cameras.json</code> (HF-schema camera array), and an
      <code>images/</code> directory with one source photo per camera.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Registered Mip-NeRF 360 scene.</strong> Pass the scene
      name (<code>bicycle</code>, <code>garden</code>,
      <code>stump</code>, <code>bonsai</code>, <code>kitchen</code>,
      <code>room</code>, <code>treehill</code>, <code>flowers</code>,
      <code>counter</code>) as the <code>filename</code> field. The
      endpoint pulls cameras + photos from the standard HuggingFace +
      Google Research mirrors. This is the path used by the SplatForge
      M3 validation harness.
    </li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Anti-claims</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Not an "outdoor preset".</strong> The encoder works on any
      scene; outdoor is just where the dB-headroom is largest. The
      product framing is "per-scene service that lands biggest on
      outdoor", not "outdoor codec".
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Not a shared trained model.</strong> Every request fits
      from scratch. There is nothing transferable; you pay for
      per-scene compute every time.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>50× headline missed.</strong> The internal M3 stretch
      target was 50× lossless median. The shipped numbers are 4-8× at
      meaningful +ΔPSNR — kept in the customer picker because that's
      still best-of-class when scene-specific fitting cost is
      acceptable.
    </li>
  </ul>
</Base>
